 All right. Hope everybody had a good lunch.

3
00:00:05,000 --> 00:00:09,000
 Well, not too good, hopefully, and then you fall asleep and all that kind of stuff, you know.

4
00:00:09,000 --> 00:00:14,000
 But as you know, we've been walking through our sermon series in this season.

5
00:00:14,000 --> 00:00:16,000
 We've been calling Public Faith.

6
00:00:16,000 --> 00:00:22,000
 And in this Public Faith series, we've been exploring different areas of our lives, right?

7
00:00:22,000 --> 00:00:27,000
 Where we are applying the idea of how do we present our faith more publicly?

8
00:00:27,000 --> 00:00:34,000
 How do we live more genuine lives of faith in the different parts of our everyday life?

9
00:00:34,000 --> 00:00:36,000
 So we've talked about parenting. We talked about ambition.

10
00:00:36,000 --> 00:00:41,000
 We talked about the workplace. And today we're talking about relationships.

11
00:00:41,000 --> 00:00:44,000
 That's the theme for today. Relationships.

12
00:00:44,000 --> 00:00:51,000
 Now, most of us here have probably got some sort of social media platform or following and stuff like that.

13
00:00:51,000 --> 00:00:54,000
 You know, we stroll through Instagram. It's quite common thing to do.

14
00:00:54,000 --> 00:01:04,000
 But can you remember the very first, you know, what was your first interaction with social media like way back in the day?

15
00:01:04,000 --> 00:01:08,000
 I remember back when we still had dial-up Internet.

16
00:01:08,000 --> 00:01:14,000
 You remember dial-up Internet where you log on the modem and go.

17
00:01:14,000 --> 00:01:18,000
 And then it sounds like you're trying to drown a cat when trying to log on to the World Wide Web.

18
00:01:18,000 --> 00:01:23,000
 And then you have to pray really hard that as you online, nobody would call the home phone.

19
00:01:23,000 --> 00:01:27,000
 Because then it would cut off the Internet and you have to start reading all over again.

20
00:01:27,000 --> 00:01:33,000
 And so when I, you know, when I was first discovering the Internet, there was two things that I would often do on the Internet.

21
00:01:33,000 --> 00:01:37,000
 First was visit. There's this very interesting site called LimeWire.

22
00:01:37,000 --> 00:01:41,000
 Right. You guys remember LimeWire. Right. OK. Right.

23
00:01:41,000 --> 00:01:46,000
 If you do, it might not be reflected well on you because LimeWire was where you could get free music.

24
00:01:46,000 --> 00:01:51,000
 OK. We'll just leave it at that. OK. It wasn't really free. Probably the safest way to describe that, though.

25
00:01:51,000 --> 00:01:59,000
 But the next place I would log on to, there was there was a platform there which is probably familiar to you guys.

26
00:01:59,000 --> 00:02:03,000
 Actually, if you heard the sound, you might recognize it straight away.

27
00:02:03,000 --> 00:02:07,000
 If we could play that sound, please recognize what that is. Oh, right.

28
00:02:07,000 --> 00:02:13,000
 There's somebody, you know, right. I see Q. OK. One of the first social media platforms.

29
00:02:13,000 --> 00:02:17,000
 If you're millennial in this place today. Right. You probably will remember that.

30
00:02:17,000 --> 00:02:22,000
 So every time I hear that noise, I'm taken back. Oh, yeah. Thank you.

31
00:02:22,000 --> 00:02:28,000
 Oh, nostalgia. OK. Every time I hear that, I'm taken back to a preteen Ellison.

32
00:02:28,000 --> 00:02:32,000
 OK. I'm sitting in the living room of my house. I was the only place with a computer.

33
00:02:32,000 --> 00:02:36,000
 Right. In the living room. Right. The monitors that as big as a refrigerator.

34
00:02:36,000 --> 00:02:42,000
 Right. This huge box on top of the on top of the desk. And I would log on to I.C.Q.

35
00:02:42,000 --> 00:02:48,000
 It was late at night. Everyone else was asleep. It's just me and the warm, comforting glow of the monitor.

36
00:02:48,000 --> 00:02:53,000
 Right. And I.C.Q. was like the original social media platform.

37
00:02:53,000 --> 00:02:59,000
 Right. An instant messaging place where you could chat with your friends, but also connect with people from all over the world.

38
00:02:59,000 --> 00:03:06,000
 So every night I would go right. Sign into I.C.Q. waiting for my crush to log on at the same time.

39
00:03:06,000 --> 00:03:12,000
 Waiting for her to message me. Right. And so that Oh sound. Right. Would be notification that Louisa.

40
00:03:12,000 --> 00:03:16,000
 Her name was Louisa. Louisa was online. OK. And she sent me a message. Right.

41
00:03:16,000 --> 00:03:21,000
 And so she sent me a message. You know, a little flutter of excitement. We're talking again. Right.

42
00:03:21,000 --> 00:03:25,000
 And that was chatting away. And we would talk for hours on I.C.Q.

43
00:03:25,000 --> 00:03:31,000
 Right. Sharing our deepest, darkest secrets with each other. Right. Declaring our puppy love.

44
00:03:31,000 --> 00:03:36,000
 You know, I think I had pretty good game on I.C.Q. Right. I was funny. I was clever. Right.

45
00:03:36,000 --> 00:03:45,000
 Kind of romantic, a bit cheeky, kind of confident. All the characteristics, like stereotypically makes a girl want to talk to a guy, I guess.

46
00:03:45,000 --> 00:03:52,000
 Right. So it was confusing for me that when I got back to school the next day, every time I go back to school, I would say, hey, how's it going?

47
00:03:52,000 --> 00:03:57,000
 That was fun chatting last night. Right. She would look at me like, what are you talking to me? Right.

48
00:03:57,000 --> 00:04:02,000
 You completely ignore me. Right. Maybe it's because I was like three foot two at the time, even shorter than I was.

49
00:04:02,000 --> 00:04:06,000
 And with this squeaky voice like you go through, we're going through puberty.

50
00:04:06,000 --> 00:04:12,000
 And she was like the popular girl that everybody liked. So, you know, it was always awkward for me.

51
00:04:12,000 --> 00:04:24,000
 But that was when I realized something. I realized that when you're online, right, there's this weird power and a mystery to being behind a screen and a keyboard.

52
00:04:24,000 --> 00:04:29,000
 You see behind the screen and the keyboard, you can be whoever you want to be.

53
00:04:29,000 --> 00:04:36,000
 You can talk to whoever you wanted to say whatever you wanted to say. But that doesn't always translate back into real life.

54
00:04:36,000 --> 00:04:47,000
 And over the years, as the Internet has developed and social media platforms get more sophisticated, the power and the ability to be a totally different person on screen,

55
00:04:47,000 --> 00:04:59,000
 behind the screen and a keyboard is only increased. And in general, I think this has had a negative impact on our humanity and our relationships.

56
00:04:59,000 --> 00:05:03,000
 Now, don't get me wrong. You know, social media is a lot. There's a lot of good stuff that comes out of it.

57
00:05:03,000 --> 00:05:08,000
 It's a fun place to hang out, showcase stuff, you know, different things to discover.

58
00:05:08,000 --> 00:05:15,000
 But there is a danger to it as well. Right. Just look through the comment sections of some of these Instagram posts.

59
00:05:15,000 --> 00:05:28,000
 Right. The most normal Instagram posts can attract all these rude, mean, ugly, racist, nasty, sexist, homophobic, just all around horrible comments attached to a simple picture.

60
00:05:28,000 --> 00:05:38,000
 And people say things they would never say to you if they were face to face. Right. And suddenly you're online. Right. But you have no fear. Right. Because you're online.

61
00:05:38,000 --> 00:05:51,000
 Sociologists call this the online disinhibitation effect. The idea is we feel bolder to say these wild and awful things online because of a few areas, because a few reasons.

62
00:05:51,000 --> 00:05:59,000
 First, there's anonymity. Right. Nobody really knows who you are. You can even create a fake account just to do stuff like this. Right.

63
00:05:59,000 --> 00:06:09,000
 There's an invisibility. They can't really see you and you can't really see the damage that you're causing to someone else as you're dropping these nasty comments.

64
00:06:09,000 --> 00:06:15,000
 Right. There's something also called asynchronicity, which means there's a delayed response.

65
00:06:15,000 --> 00:06:19,000
 So, you know, now, if you know, if you're empty, are you bumped into someone? They bump you back. Right. There's a response straight away.

66
00:06:19,000 --> 00:06:28,000
 But online, you don't get that. Right. There's a delayed response. And then there's also no real sense of authority. Right. Who owns Internet? Right.

67
00:06:28,000 --> 00:06:32,000
 Nobody really. And so when there's no authority, right, people act wild.

68
00:06:32,000 --> 00:06:37,000
 Just watch a bunch of kids in a classroom without any authority or any group of people without any authority.

69
00:06:37,000 --> 00:06:47,000
 Things tend to get out of hand. So that's one way of social media, I feel like, has been negatively impacting our relationships.

70
00:06:47,000 --> 00:06:57,000
 Another way, though, is that most of the time, a lot of the time, maybe online and on social media, we have control over what we want people to see.

71
00:06:57,000 --> 00:07:04,000
 And so our social media pages and our social media spaces often make it seem like everything is perfect.

72
00:07:04,000 --> 00:07:14,000
 Right. Everyone leaves, lives these stress free, you know, luxury holidays, fast cars, nice clothes, beautiful people, fancy restaurants, obedient children.

73
00:07:14,000 --> 00:07:26,000
 Right. And we convey this sort of world that is so distorted from what reality actually is, because the reality is, of course, nobody's immune to stress and to hard times.

74
00:07:26,000 --> 00:07:36,000
 And to brokenness and to struggles. But when all we do is showcase highlights, it puts up a barrier to us in relationships.

75
00:07:36,000 --> 00:07:44,000
 And because of this, it feels feelings of envy and jealousy and even resentment towards each other.

76
00:07:44,000 --> 00:07:52,000
 And so now, right in this day and age, as followers of Jesus, navigating the online world can be challenging.

77
00:07:52,000 --> 00:07:57,000
 It's very easy to get caught up in the negativity, especially when you throw scroll through a few of those comments.

78
00:07:57,000 --> 00:08:02,000
 Right. It's easy to get caught up in the negativity of that space.

79
00:08:02,000 --> 00:08:09,000
 And at the same time, it's easy to give in to the pressure to make our lives look like they're perfect.

80
00:08:09,000 --> 00:08:21,000
 And very soon when we start functioning that way, our online presence bears very little resemblance about our real life following of Jesus.

81
00:08:21,000 --> 00:08:28,000
 And then we struggle. We find out we struggle. We are kind of meet anyone like, you know, it's such a nasty like, why is that happening?

82
00:08:28,000 --> 00:08:32,000
 Now, of course, these issues aren't just limited to online. Right.

83
00:08:32,000 --> 00:08:38,000
 But in our daily in-person face to face relationships, those are struggling as well.

84
00:08:38,000 --> 00:08:45,000
 In the beginning of the series, Andrew talked to us about the fact that we're supposed to be salt and light in this world, if you remember. Right.

85
00:08:45,000 --> 00:08:52,000
 Salt and light are what Jesus's followers, his disciples are called to be.

86
00:08:52,000 --> 00:08:56,000
 We're supposed to be the ones who bring the flavor of Jesus to the broken world.

87
00:08:56,000 --> 00:09:04,000
 We're the ones that are supposed to bring the light of Jesus to shine wherever we see sin and darkness and brokenness.

88
00:09:04,000 --> 00:09:09,000
 But if we want to do that, it's going to take standing out.

89
00:09:09,000 --> 00:09:16,000
 It means fighting for and believing in and speaking up on things that go against popular culture.

90
00:09:16,000 --> 00:09:22,000
 And that is hard. That is hard. So instead, we feel the pressure to blend in.

91
00:09:22,000 --> 00:09:29,000
 We lose our saltiness. We dim our light and we begin to conform to the world.

92
00:09:29,000 --> 00:09:36,000
 And for many people, this might take different, you know, the context is a bit different.

93
00:09:36,000 --> 00:09:46,000
 Maybe you're at school. Right. And the normal thing for people to do at school on the weekends or whenever, right, on holidays is for people to go out, go parties, get drunk and make terrible decisions.

94
00:09:46,000 --> 00:09:55,000
 Right. Doing things that you know are wrong. But you feel like you have to do that because if everyone else is doing it right, you're going to be left out.

95
00:09:55,000 --> 00:09:59,000
 And nobody wants to be like the goody two shoes, like the party pooper. Right.

96
00:09:59,000 --> 00:10:06,000
 And that doesn't get involved in the parties. Right. People would just think, oh, that's a good Christian boy or girl. No fun to hang out with.

97
00:10:06,000 --> 00:10:17,000
 Who wants to hang out with that person? Right. Maybe you're in a romantic relationship and there's the pressure there to be sexually intimate without being married or before getting married.

98
00:10:17,000 --> 00:10:23,000
 Right. Go and do it, of course. Right. Everyone's doing it. You know, it's all over the culture. It's all over the movies. Right.

99
00:10:23,000 --> 00:10:32,000
 What kind of prude, corny, backwards thinking are you stuck in to think that sexual intimacy is only for marriage?

100
00:10:32,000 --> 00:10:42,000
 Or maybe like Pastor Jennifer was saying last week at your workplace and your relationship with your colleagues and your boss, right, dishonest practices are just commonplace.

101
00:10:42,000 --> 00:10:50,000
 People don't value the truth. They don't value honesty. And if you don't follow suit, you're going to be the one that costs the team that bonus check at the end of the month.

102
00:10:50,000 --> 00:10:57,000
 Right. Who's going to want to work with somebody like that? So here's our problem.

103
00:10:57,000 --> 00:11:05,000
 Because, you know, we want relationships. And because we want relationships, we get tempted and sometimes we even do conform.

104
00:11:05,000 --> 00:11:12,000
 We change who we are. We compromise our faith in Jesus. And because we're constantly changing, it becomes even confusing for ourselves.

105
00:11:12,000 --> 00:11:19,000
 Like, who am I really? You don't even know anymore. Right. Often we get we get so lost in the world.

106
00:11:19,000 --> 00:11:26,000
 Which version of me am I supposed to be? The online version? The one at work, the one at church, the one in my family.

107
00:11:26,000 --> 00:11:40,000
 And in trying to fit in, we lose ourselves in the process. And if nobody's being real, how can we possibly have meaningful relationship with each other?

108
00:11:40,000 --> 00:11:46,000
 Now, it's a huge problem because it goes against how God wants us to live.

109
00:11:46,000 --> 00:11:54,000
 Here's the truth. The truth is you and I and everyone else in this world are made in the image of God.

110
00:11:54,000 --> 00:12:06,000
 And he made us the way he made us was to be in deep, meaningful, genuine, life-giving, joyful relationships with him, first of all, and then with each other.

111
00:12:06,000 --> 00:12:14,000
 This is the way we've been designed. This is the way we've been created. This is why we crave relationships.

112
00:12:14,000 --> 00:12:20,000
 Go back to Genesis when God was doing his thing right in the beginning of time, creating the heavens and the earth.

113
00:12:20,000 --> 00:12:30,000
 After each day, after each section of work, he declared it good. Light and darkness. Good. Sky and land. Good. Sun, moon and planets. Good.

114
00:12:30,000 --> 00:12:39,000
 Fish and the sea animals and the land. Good. Human beings. Good. It was all very good when creation was completed.

115
00:12:39,000 --> 00:12:49,000
 Apart from one thing. In this perfectly created universe, there was one thing God said was not good.

116
00:12:49,000 --> 00:13:00,000
 And that was loneliness. He tells us it is not good for the man to be alone. I will make a helper suitable for him.

117
00:13:00,000 --> 00:13:09,000
 And so out of that, Eve is created. And Adam and Eve, she and Adam have this flourishing, deep, authentic, vulnerable relationship with each other.

118
00:13:09,000 --> 00:13:15,000
 We know this because the Bible tells us that they were together. They were naked and they were unashamed.

119
00:13:15,000 --> 00:13:27,000
 Right. So there was this complete truth, complete honesty, complete vulnerability, this perfect community they had, first of all, with their creator and then also with each other.

120
00:13:27,000 --> 00:13:31,000
 And like I said just now, this is why we crave real and deep relationships.

121
00:13:31,000 --> 00:13:36,000
 It's because we've been designed and created so that it's not good for us to be alone.

122
00:13:36,000 --> 00:13:46,000
 God made us to be with each other, which means that the true potential of any relationship is only realized when those relationships,

123
00:13:46,000 --> 00:13:54,000
 the one we have with God and the one we have with each other, are going back to his original plan and purposes for them.

124
00:13:54,000 --> 00:13:59,000
 But the problem is this, right? Sin has completely messed up our relationships.

125
00:13:59,000 --> 00:14:10,000
 Sin has completely messed up everything in our lives. The enemy has come to rob, kill and destroy our connection with God and our connection with each other.

126
00:14:10,000 --> 00:14:17,000
 This is why when we conform to the world, we lose who God created us to be.

127
00:14:17,000 --> 00:14:26,000
 And it shouldn't be surprising, right? Because if the whole process of us building a relationship with each other is a version that you've created of yourself,

128
00:14:26,000 --> 00:14:32,000
 not the real you that God has created you to be, then of course it's not going to work.

129
00:14:32,000 --> 00:14:36,000
 But because the whole foundation of this has been a lie.

130
00:14:36,000 --> 00:14:44,000
 If you've literally had to change everything about yourself so that you would fit into a group, make this person like you or make that person want to date you,

131
00:14:44,000 --> 00:14:52,000
 and then you suddenly find yourself struggling in relationships, unfulfilled, it feels shallow, you know it's being fake.

132
00:14:52,000 --> 00:14:58,000
 And eventually we feel that sort of heaviness on us, right? It becomes unbearable.

133
00:14:58,000 --> 00:15:04,000
 This is because God did not create us to approach relationships in this way.

134
00:15:04,000 --> 00:15:12,000
 And instead of being these life-giving, joyful things, relationships have become a deep source of pain.

135
00:15:12,000 --> 00:15:18,000
 Relationships have even become a way we use to hurt each other.

136
00:15:18,000 --> 00:15:23,000
 And sin has so poisoned how we relate to each other that we now cannot be ourselves.

137
00:15:23,000 --> 00:15:31,000
 We cannot come before each other unashamedly, in vulnerability and in authenticity.

138
00:15:31,000 --> 00:15:35,000
 The good news is though, there is a better way.

139
00:15:35,000 --> 00:15:43,000
 And what the enemy comes to rob, kill and destroy, Jesus says he comes to give us life and life to the full.

140
00:15:43,000 --> 00:15:54,000
 And that full life is found when our relationships aren't shaped by the world and its culture, but rooted in the real love of God.

141
00:15:54,000 --> 00:15:59,000
 And the gospel is that we know what this love looks like.

142
00:15:59,000 --> 00:16:08,000
 Scripture gives us clear pictures and good guidelines of how to live out this relationship, these genuine relationships that God wants us to have.

143
00:16:08,000 --> 00:16:17,000
 Romans 12, 9 tells us this, "Love must be sincere. Hate what is evil, cling to what is good."

144
00:16:17,000 --> 00:16:21,000
 First, let's look at this. Love must be sincere.

145
00:16:21,000 --> 00:16:26,000
 Now, growing up in Hong Kong, every time I hear the word sincere, I always think about the department store.

146
00:16:26,000 --> 00:16:31,000
 It's just a natural reaction. We're not talking about the shopping and department stores.

147
00:16:31,000 --> 00:16:42,000
 Sincere here means free from pretense and deceit, proceeding from genuine feelings.

148
00:16:42,000 --> 00:16:51,000
 Fake love can be one of the most damaging things that we can do to each other.

149
00:16:51,000 --> 00:17:02,000
 And some of us have taken advantage of people we know are looking for love, looking for acceptance, connection, and friendship.

150
00:17:02,000 --> 00:17:09,000
 We've seen vulnerable people, and we know the right words to say.

151
00:17:09,000 --> 00:17:12,000
 We know the right way to pretend to care.

152
00:17:12,000 --> 00:17:17,000
 But meanwhile, we also know that all that, this is just fake. There's nothing genuine about this.

153
00:17:17,000 --> 00:17:28,000
 None of it is real. And our aim is to manipulate and deceive others with a false sense of love so that we can get what we want.

154
00:17:28,000 --> 00:17:35,000
 I said this in the second service. I think it goes for all of us at all times too.

155
00:17:35,000 --> 00:17:40,000
 And if that is you in this community here today, I want you to hear me very carefully.

156
00:17:40,000 --> 00:17:46,000
 There is no place for that in this church, in this community.

157
00:17:46,000 --> 00:17:50,000
 You're welcome to come and worship. You're welcome to come and be a part.

158
00:17:50,000 --> 00:18:00,000
 But if you are going to use this place as a way to seek out vulnerable people, to take advantage of them,

159
00:18:00,000 --> 00:18:07,000
 misuse trust that people give to you, that is not going to be accepted in this community.

160
00:18:07,000 --> 00:18:12,000
 Because for some of us, we have been the victims of that.

161
00:18:12,000 --> 00:18:18,000
 We've given ourselves away to someone else because we believe that their love for us was sincere when it wasn't.

162
00:18:18,000 --> 00:18:26,000
 We've heard the words, we felt the feelings. So we give our time, our trust, our money, our resources, our feelings, our bodies.

163
00:18:26,000 --> 00:18:31,000
 We give up ourselves only to find out that it was all a lie.

164
00:18:31,000 --> 00:18:37,000
 And when that happens to us, it's hurtful and it's damaging.

165
00:18:37,000 --> 00:18:48,000
 And sometimes it hurts so much that we feel like we never want to open ourselves up ever again for the fear of being hurt once more.

166
00:18:48,000 --> 00:18:53,000
 But here's the thing about God's love. There is nothing fake about God's love.

167
00:18:53,000 --> 00:18:58,000
 God doesn't just tell us that he loves us. He shows it to us time and time again.

168
00:18:58,000 --> 00:19:05,000
 You might argue that the entirety of Scripture, the entirety of all the stories that put together that we have in our Bibles,

169
00:19:05,000 --> 00:19:10,000
 are countless examples of how God demonstrates his love for humanity.

170
00:19:10,000 --> 00:19:15,000
 Before the flood hits the world, he tells Noah, "Build an ark, right? Save yourself.

171
00:19:15,000 --> 00:19:19,000
 I'm showing you my love by telling you, by warning you, the flood is coming.

172
00:19:19,000 --> 00:19:22,000
 Build an ark, keep you and your family safe."

173
00:19:22,000 --> 00:19:30,000
 He leads the Israelites out of slavery and provides everything that they could possibly need in the most desolate of places in the wilderness.

174
00:19:30,000 --> 00:19:35,000
 He gives food, he gives water, he guides them into the promised land.

175
00:19:35,000 --> 00:19:40,000
 When people don't have strength, he steps in personally and fights battles for them.

176
00:19:40,000 --> 00:19:47,000
 He sends prophets with messages of warning and promises and of comfort of his love.

177
00:19:47,000 --> 00:19:51,000
 He declares to us that his love reaches to a thousand generations.

178
00:19:51,000 --> 00:19:56,000
 This really is just a hyperbole for his love for us is never ending.

179
00:19:56,000 --> 00:19:59,000
 It goes on and on and on and on.

180
00:19:59,000 --> 00:20:06,000
 He refuses to give up on human beings, even though time and time again, we rebel against him.

181
00:20:06,000 --> 00:20:15,000
 And ultimately, God showed his love for us by becoming flesh, by sending Jesus to come and walk on this earth.

182
00:20:15,000 --> 00:20:21,000
 And Jesus, as our Savior, becomes the perfect example of what love is.

183
00:20:21,000 --> 00:20:32,000
 A love that reaches out to everybody, a love which is not scared to get involved in the hurts and pains of broken people instead of keeping them at arm's length.

184
00:20:32,000 --> 00:20:37,000
 A love which was willing to sacrifice his own life.

185
00:20:37,000 --> 00:20:45,000
 And Jesus goes to the cross as a loving sacrifice for the consequences of our sins.

186
00:20:45,000 --> 00:20:50,000
 This is why when Paul tells us about what love is, he is obviously thinking about Jesus, right?

187
00:20:50,000 --> 00:20:52,000
 He says these are the qualities of love.

188
00:20:52,000 --> 00:20:58,000
 Love is patient. Love is kind. It does not envy. It does not boast. It is not proud.

189
00:20:58,000 --> 00:21:03,000
 It does not dishonor others. It is not self-seeking. It is not easily angered.

190
00:21:03,000 --> 00:21:08,000
 It keeps no record of wrongs. Love does not delight in evil, but always rejoices with the truth.

191
00:21:08,000 --> 00:21:13,000
 It always protects, always trust, always hope, always perseveres.

192
00:21:13,000 --> 00:21:16,000
 Love never fails.

193
00:21:16,000 --> 00:21:28,000
 This is the kind of love that God has for us, which means that this is the kind of love that he wants us to display to each other in relationship.

194
00:21:28,000 --> 00:21:32,000
 Right. This is sincere love. That's what it looks like.

195
00:21:32,000 --> 00:21:36,000
 But Paul doesn't stop there. He says this love must be sincere.

196
00:21:36,000 --> 00:21:41,000
 The next step of that is we have to hate what is evil.

197
00:21:41,000 --> 00:21:43,000
 And why is that?

198
00:21:43,000 --> 00:21:53,000
 Well, we cannot truly love each other if we're not willing to confront the very things that threaten to ruin that love.

199
00:21:53,000 --> 00:21:58,000
 Real love has to take a stand against the evil.

200
00:21:58,000 --> 00:22:02,000
 We cannot just sit idly by and do nothing about it.

201
00:22:02,000 --> 00:22:11,000
 We cannot ignore the things that are threatening to tear people apart.

202
00:22:11,000 --> 00:22:20,000
 And we need to be reminded about this, because if we're honest, all of us in this room would probably say, I mean, hopefully nobody in this room would say, oh, yeah, I love doing evil things.

203
00:22:20,000 --> 00:22:27,000
 I've spent all my time plotting evil, you know, like, thinking in the brain, you know, and I just want to do evil things all the time.

204
00:22:27,000 --> 00:22:33,000
 But at the same time, right, on some level, I think we all wrestle with it.

205
00:22:33,000 --> 00:22:37,000
 We have a certain fascination with sin.

206
00:22:37,000 --> 00:22:43,000
 And like I said, it's because sin and evil have infected every aspect of our lives.

207
00:22:43,000 --> 00:22:52,000
 And like we've been talking about, the very presence of evil in this world is precisely why it's so hard to be in relationship with each other.

208
00:22:52,000 --> 00:22:56,000
 It's why relationships can sometimes be a struggle.

209
00:22:56,000 --> 00:23:01,000
 So what is evil? What are these things that God hates?

210
00:23:01,000 --> 00:23:06,000
 Well, good thing for us, Scripture also gives us a very clear picture of these things.

211
00:23:06,000 --> 00:23:09,000
 Proverbs 6 tells us this.

212
00:23:09,000 --> 00:23:13,000
 "They are six things that the Lord hates," right? Doesn't get more clear than that.

213
00:23:13,000 --> 00:23:16,000
 "Seven that are detestable to him.

214
00:23:16,000 --> 00:23:32,000
 Haughty eyes, a lying tongue, hands that shed innocent blood, a heart that divides his wicked schemes, feet that are quick to rush into evil, a false witness who pours out lies, and a person who stirs up conflict in the community."

215
00:23:32,000 --> 00:23:39,000
 Now, if you look at this list, you'll notice that there's a common thread that runs through it.

216
00:23:39,000 --> 00:23:47,000
 Every single one of these evil characteristics are things that are detrimental to our personal relationships.

217
00:23:47,000 --> 00:23:51,000
 "Haughty eyes" means people who are arrogant.

218
00:23:51,000 --> 00:23:57,000
 "Haughty eyes" are people who are arrogant and think they are above everybody else.

219
00:23:57,000 --> 00:24:06,000
 "A lying tongue" is not just those who speak words that are not true, but it's those who try and twist the truth for their own gain.

220
00:24:06,000 --> 00:24:12,000
 "Hands that shed innocent blood" are people who are unable to control their anger, right?

221
00:24:12,000 --> 00:24:18,000
 Always angry at any moment to the point where they're willing to get violent.

222
00:24:18,000 --> 00:24:27,000
 "A heart that divides his wicked schemes" are those that will compromise their values if it will work out to their own advantage.

223
00:24:27,000 --> 00:24:38,000
 "Feet that rush towards evil" are those who look forward to opportunities of doing wrong and then hiding in the shadows and getting away with it.

224
00:24:38,000 --> 00:24:50,000
 "False witnesses" refers to those who don't uphold justice, who are willing to trample on other people and oppress them so that they can get the advantage in life.

225
00:24:50,000 --> 00:24:55,000
 And the person who stirs up conflict is the one who attempts to break up these building blocks,

226
00:24:55,000 --> 00:25:03,000
 these foundations of trust and of love and of friendship that hold society together.

227
00:25:03,000 --> 00:25:09,000
 Now you tell me, does this sound like the kind of person that you would like to be?

228
00:25:09,000 --> 00:25:15,000
 Does this sound like the kind of people that you would want to be in relationship with?

229
00:25:15,000 --> 00:25:20,000
 But again, if we're honest, and you know, I had to do a lot of honest thinking in the preparation for this as well.

230
00:25:20,000 --> 00:25:28,000
 Sometimes we do embrace these characteristics over the characteristics of genuine love.

231
00:25:28,000 --> 00:25:36,000
 And for myself, as I was reflecting, these things are tempting to cling on to rather than love.

232
00:25:36,000 --> 00:25:44,000
 So one area I found myself sort of thinking about in my wrestling was when it talked about haughty eyes or being arrogant.

233
00:25:44,000 --> 00:25:48,000
 Because I find it very hard not to judge things.

234
00:25:48,000 --> 00:25:56,000
 When I look at a situation or I see something, one of my instant reactions normally is judgment.

235
00:25:56,000 --> 00:25:59,000
 I think, oh, I could do a better job than that.

236
00:25:59,000 --> 00:26:02,000
 Often it's when it comes to preaching, to be honest.

237
00:26:02,000 --> 00:26:10,000
 I look at, you know, when I see other preachers on Instagram or on Facebook or things like that on YouTube, right?

238
00:26:10,000 --> 00:26:15,000
 And sit there and listen, I'm thinking things like, ah, you know, that's not really right.

239
00:26:15,000 --> 00:26:17,000
 Right. Or I usually said that a different way.

240
00:26:17,000 --> 00:26:24,000
 Or did this person even study the text because it's not, you know, he's not doing the right things or she's not doing the right things and all that kind of stuff.

241
00:26:24,000 --> 00:26:33,000
 And what starts as general critique often takes an ugly term to me thinking I'm much better than that person.

242
00:26:33,000 --> 00:26:37,000
 Or a heart that devises wicked schemes.

243
00:26:37,000 --> 00:26:42,000
 Excuse me. I try my very best to be a person of integrity.

244
00:26:42,000 --> 00:26:49,000
 But I also know because of my position as a trusted member of this community.

245
00:26:49,000 --> 00:26:59,000
 Right. It's easy for me to take people's trust and twist and turn things to my own advantage because there is a natural trust that people give to me.

246
00:26:59,000 --> 00:27:08,000
 And I have to really watch myself. I feel sometimes not to abuse people's trust and twist and turn things for my own advantage.

247
00:27:08,000 --> 00:27:11,000
 I don't know what you're wrestling with. Is this for you personally?

248
00:27:11,000 --> 00:27:21,000
 What I do know, it's not easy. And building relationships that reflect God's love is going to be a battle.

249
00:27:21,000 --> 00:27:25,000
 We're going to be fighting every day against our own sinful tendencies.

250
00:27:25,000 --> 00:27:31,000
 We're going to have to be willing of things like the evil things that we hold on to.

251
00:27:31,000 --> 00:27:38,000
 So how do we fight for this? How do we get back to these relationships that God wants us to have?

252
00:27:38,000 --> 00:27:45,000
 Well, the passage tells us to do this. Cling on to what is good. Cling on to what is good.

253
00:27:45,000 --> 00:27:54,000
 Cling on means to hold on to for dear life. You know, hold on with everything you have to what is good.

254
00:27:54,000 --> 00:27:59,000
 Well, what is good then? Well, we talked about it just now. Jesus.

255
00:27:59,000 --> 00:28:05,000
 Jesus is the definition of goodness. And Jesus doesn't just call us to live differently.

256
00:28:05,000 --> 00:28:09,000
 Right. When we hold on to Jesus, we get empowered to live differently.

257
00:28:09,000 --> 00:28:13,000
 We get empowered to approach our relationships in a different way.

258
00:28:13,000 --> 00:28:21,000
 If we don't do it on our own strength, we do it with the strength that he gives to us.

259
00:28:21,000 --> 00:28:24,000
 2 Peter 1, 3 to 4 will tell it this way.

260
00:28:24,000 --> 00:28:34,000
 The divine power he has given us, everything we need for a godly life through our knowledge of him,

261
00:28:34,000 --> 00:28:38,000
 who has called us to his own glory and goodness.

262
00:28:38,000 --> 00:28:45,000
 To these he has given us a very great and precious promise, so that through them you may participate in the divine nature,

263
00:28:45,000 --> 00:28:52,000
 having escaped the corruption of the world caused by evil desires.

264
00:28:52,000 --> 00:28:59,000
 In other words, if we want to get back to the kind of relationships that are built on pure, holy, godly love,

265
00:28:59,000 --> 00:29:04,000
 the kind of relationships that we were created for, we can.

266
00:29:04,000 --> 00:29:11,000
 This is a picture that we can build, but only through his power.

267
00:29:11,000 --> 00:29:14,000
 Now, this is an important point to keep in mind.

268
00:29:14,000 --> 00:29:22,000
 I say that because one of the dangers when we start talking about things like better relationships and better work things and all that kind of stuff, right,

269
00:29:22,000 --> 00:29:26,000
 is that it can start to sound a little bit like self-help.

270
00:29:26,000 --> 00:29:30,000
 Okay, this is not self-help church.

271
00:29:30,000 --> 00:29:32,000
 I'm not talking about self-help.

272
00:29:32,000 --> 00:29:41,000
 Self-help will tell us that if you want better relationships, just pick up yourselves a little bit, make yourself, be a better yourself, make a better version of yourself.

273
00:29:41,000 --> 00:29:44,000
 And listen, you can go do that right now.

274
00:29:44,000 --> 00:29:52,000
 There are thousands and thousands of self-help books, courses, conferences to make you so-called better person.

275
00:29:52,000 --> 00:29:57,000
 And yes, maybe your relationships might improve at the same time.

276
00:29:57,000 --> 00:29:59,000
 But here's the thing.

277
00:29:59,000 --> 00:30:04,000
 Self-help will only get you so far in this world.

278
00:30:04,000 --> 00:30:11,000
 But the gospel is the salvation in this life and the next.

279
00:30:11,000 --> 00:30:15,000
 Remember, the whole point of this series, right, we're calling it public faith.

280
00:30:15,000 --> 00:30:21,000
 And public faith is not so that people will look at us and say, "Oh, look what a great person that we have."

281
00:30:21,000 --> 00:30:24,000
 There's no gospel power in that, right?

282
00:30:24,000 --> 00:30:31,000
 The whole point of this public faith series is that we are preaching the gospel with our lives.

283
00:30:31,000 --> 00:30:39,000
 So that whether it's in parenting and work and ambition and yes, in our relationships, people will see us and not say, "Oh, what a great person."

284
00:30:39,000 --> 00:30:44,000
 But people will see us and say, "Oh my goodness, I see Jesus in that person."

285
00:30:44,000 --> 00:30:48,000
 And if that's what a relationship with Jesus looks like, I want to be like that.

286
00:30:48,000 --> 00:30:52,000
 I want to know who Jesus is too.

287
00:30:52,000 --> 00:31:00,000
 And when we have relationships like this, suddenly the need to conform goes away.

288
00:31:00,000 --> 00:31:02,000
 Because we don't need to conform anymore.

289
00:31:02,000 --> 00:31:09,000
 We can tell everybody, "Come as you are," because that's how Jesus welcomes us.

290
00:31:09,000 --> 00:31:18,000
 When we have relationships like this, these are the kind of relationships where we're willing to sacrifice each other, not to take from each other.

291
00:31:18,000 --> 00:31:24,000
 When we have relationships like this, we can rejoice as well as mourn with each other.

292
00:31:24,000 --> 00:31:33,000
 When we have relationships like this, our goal becomes how to out-honor each other, not how to take one step ahead of the other person.

293
00:31:33,000 --> 00:31:49,000
 When we have relationships like this, we don't have to pretend like life is perfect anymore, but we can come with every ounce of brokenness and vulnerability and emptiness and find loving acceptance.

294
00:31:49,000 --> 00:31:58,000
 When we have relations like this, people will see that Jesus is the reason.

295
00:31:58,000 --> 00:32:01,000
 This isn't just about better relationships.

296
00:32:01,000 --> 00:32:04,000
 It's about our witness.

297
00:32:04,000 --> 00:32:11,000
 And when the world looks at us, they're deciding what they believe about Jesus based upon how we love.

298
00:32:11,000 --> 00:32:21,000
 And so our job now is to continue to hate what is evil, deal with sin and all the brokenness in our lives and in this world.

299
00:32:21,000 --> 00:32:32,000
 We cling to what is good so that people can tell we are Christians by the way we love each other.

300
00:32:32,000 --> 00:32:35,000
 Of course, this sounds kind of idealistic.

301
00:32:35,000 --> 00:32:39,000
 And the truth is we are all on a journey in this, right?

302
00:32:39,000 --> 00:32:48,000
 The challenge to live like this is something that we're going to have to keep on working on day after day, time and time again.

303
00:32:48,000 --> 00:33:00,000
 And one of the beautiful things about this series is that we've been inviting people from the community to share their experiences about what it's been like for them to navigate the different areas that we've been talking about.

